Here are both approaches for passing data during Shell navigation, received via `IQueryAttributable` on the ViewModel.

## 1. Register the route (AppShell.xaml.cs)

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
    }
}
```

## 2. Navigate from ProductListPage

```csharp
// Approach A — string query parameter (product ID only)
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

// Approach B — pass the full Product object
var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
{
    { "product", product }
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
```

## 3. Receive on the ViewModel with IQueryAttributable

```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _productId;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A — string parameter from query string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service using the ID
        }

        // Approach B — full object via ShellNavigationQueryParameters
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
            ProductId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

## 4. Wire the ViewModel to ProductDetailsPage

```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **Approach A** serializes the ID into the URI — good for simple values and deep-link-friendly.
- **Approach B** uses `ShellNavigationQueryParameters` to pass the object by reference — avoids re-fetching but isn't deep-linkable.
- Both land in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so you can support either caller seamlessly.
- Always `await` `GoToAsync` to avoid race conditions.
- Register the page with DI (`builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsPage>()`) so constructor injection works.
